  "prompt": "What is the difference between FRS, PRD, TRD, SRS, MRD, BRD?",
  "response": "These acronyms refer to various types of documents used in project management and systems development, particularly in software engineering. Each document serves a specific purpose in the lifecycle of a project:\n\n1. **FRS (Functional Requirements Specification)**: This document outlines the functions that a system or component must perform. It details the expected behavior of a system described through various use cases. FRS forms the basis for designing and testing a system.\n\n2. **PRD (Product Requirements Document)**: This is a comprehensive document outlining all the requirements of a product, including both functional and non-functional requirements. It serves as a guide for developers and stakeholders to understand what the product must achieve and how it is supposed to do so.\n\n3. **TRD (Technical Requirements Document)**: It describes the technical requirements and architecture of a system. The TRD is aimed at developers and technical architects, detailing technical aspects like system architecture, data structures, algorithms, and interfaces.\n\n4. **SRS (Software Requirements Specification)**: This document defines the software requirements and is a detailed description of the different software functions, features, constraints, interfaces, and interactions. It serves as a contract between the client and developers and is typically more detailed than an FRS.\n\n5. **MRD (Market Requirements Document)**: The MRD describes the market opportunity, customer needs, competitive landscape, and requirements of a product from a business perspective. It is often used to ensure that the developed product matches the market demands and business objectives.\n\n6. **BRD (Business Requirements Document)**: This document outlines high-level business needs and objectives that the system or project must meet. It is essential for ensuring that the project aligns with the overall business goals and strategy, often serving as a precursor to more detailed requirements documents.\n\nEach of these documents plays a vital role at different stages of product development, ensuring that all stakeholders have a clear understanding of requirements and objectives.",
